  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Slat Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Slat Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A slat conveyor uses individual rigid slats attached to two parallel roller chains to form a moving platform that transports heavy products, pallets, and assembled goods. The slats, whether steel, wood, aluminum, or plastic, provide a flat, stable surface that handles loads from 500 to over 10,000 lbs per pallet position. Slat conveyors serve automotive assembly lines, appliance manufacturing, pallet handling, and any application requiring a rigid conveying surface that resists damage from heat, sharp edges, and heavy impact that would destroy a belt conveyor.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Slat Types -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Slat Types</div>
      <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Slat Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Types</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Steel Slat Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Steel slat conveyors use carbon steel or <a href="/conveyor-types/stainless-steel-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">stainless steel</a> slats bolted to precision roller chains. Steel slats handle the heaviest loads (up to 10,000+ lbs per position), resist hot products (up to 500°F for carbon steel, 800°F for stainless), and withstand impact and abrasion from rough industrial products. Steel slat conveyors serve automotive assembly (chassis, body-in-white transport), appliance manufacturing, and heavy industrial operations. Richards-Wilcox, Pacline, and Webb-Stiles manufacture steel slat conveyor systems.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Wood Slat Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Wood slat conveyors use hardwood boards (typically oak or maple) attached to roller chains. Wood slats provide a non-marring surface for finished products, cost less than steel slats, and are easily replaced when damaged. Wood slat conveyors handle pallets, heavy cases, and furniture in manufacturing and warehousing operations. The wood surface grips pallets better than steel, reducing pallet sliding on inclines. Wood slats suit loads up to 2,000-3,000 lbs per position.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Hinged Slat (Apron) Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Hinged slat conveyors (also called apron conveyors) use overlapping steel plates that hinge at the chain connection points. The overlap prevents material from falling through the gaps between slats. Apron conveyors suit bulk material handling where a rugged, solid surface is needed: hot castings from foundry shakeout, heavy forgings, scrap metal, and demolition debris. They differ from <a href="/conveyor-types/hinged-steel-belt/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">hinged steel belt conveyors</a> by using heavier plates, larger chains, and handling substantially heavier loads per foot.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Plastic / UHMW Slat Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Plastic slat conveyors use UHMW-PE (ultra-high molecular weight polyethylene) or other engineering plastic slats. Plastic slats provide a gentle, low-friction, non-marring surface for products with finished surfaces. They suit <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food processing</a> (FDA-approved materials), cleanroom manufacturing, and applications where metal contamination is a concern. Plastic slats are lighter than steel, reduce noise, and resist corrosion from chemicals and washdown.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

