  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Slat Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Automotive assembly:</strong> Floor-level slat conveyors transport vehicle bodies through assembly stations where workers install components. The rigid, flat slat surface supports vehicle weight (3,000-6,000 lbs) without deflection. Slat speed synchronizes with the assembly takt time. Inverted power-and-free or overhead monorail systems handle the vertical transport while slat conveyors handle floor-level workstations.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Appliance manufacturing:</strong> Washers, dryers, refrigerators, and ovens ride slat conveyors through assembly, testing, and packaging stations. The rigid slat surface provides a stable work platform for heavy appliances (150-400 lbs). Workers stand alongside the conveyor and perform assembly tasks as the appliance moves past at walking pace (2-6 FPM).</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Pallet handling:</strong> Slat conveyors transport loaded pallets (up to 3,000-4,000 lbs) between <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">palletizers</a>, stretch wrappers, and dock staging areas. Wood slats grip pallet bottoms to prevent sliding. Slat conveyors handle pallets that are too heavy or too irregular for <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyors</a>.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Beverage can and bottle lines:</strong> Narrow stainless steel slat conveyors (<a href="/conveyor-types/tabletop-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">tabletop chains</a> are closely related) transport cans and bottles through filling, sealing, and pasteurization. The rigid slat surface prevents container tipping compared to rollers. Stainless steel construction handles pasteurizer temperatures and washdown environments.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Heavy case and tray handling:</strong> Slat conveyors transport heavy cases (50-200 lbs), filled totes, and loaded trays between <a href="/conveyor-functions/tray-loading/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">tray loading</a>, wrapping, and palletizing operations. The flat slat surface prevents case snagging and tipping that occur on roller conveyors with heavy, irregularly shaped loads.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Oven and kiln discharge:</strong> Steel or stainless steel slat conveyors receive hot products from oven and kiln exits. The metal slats withstand temperatures that would melt plastic belts or chains. Slat conveyors transport hot ceramics, baked goods, metal parts, and glass from thermal processing to cooling and inspection.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Design Considerations -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="design-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Engineering</div>
      <h2 id="design-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Design <span class="text-accent">Considerations</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Chain Selection</h3>
        <p>The roller chain determines the slat conveyor's load capacity, speed, and service life. Standard precision roller chains (ANSI 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160) suit most industrial slat conveyors. Heavy-duty applications use forged-link chains or engineered steel chains with greater ultimate strength. Chain pitch affects slat spacing and conveyor speed. Larger chain pitch allows heavier loads but produces coarser speed increments.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Slat Spacing &#x26; Gap</h3>
        <p>The gap between adjacent slats determines what products the conveyor can carry. Tight gaps (1/8"-1/4") prevent small parts from falling through. Wider gaps (1/2"-1") reduce slat cost and conveyor weight but limit the smallest product size. Overlapping slats (hinged/apron style) eliminate gaps entirely for bulk material handling. Slat spacing must also clear the sprocket wrap at the head and tail ends.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Speed &#x26; Indexing</h3>
        <p>Slat conveyors typically operate at low speeds: 2-30 FPM for assembly applications, 10-60 FPM for material transport. <a href="/resources/automated-conveyor-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Variable frequency drives</a> (VFDs) provide adjustable speed. For assembly operations, slat conveyors often run in index mode: the conveyor advances one station length, stops for a set work time, then advances again. Index conveyors require precise positioning using encoders and PLC control. See our <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">indexing conveyor guide</a> for details.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Return Run</h3>
        <p>The return run (underside) of a slat conveyor must clear the floor or support structure. Slat conveyors require more vertical space than belt conveyors because the rigid slats do not flex around small-diameter pulleys. Minimum sprocket diameters depend on chain pitch and slat attachment geometry. Floor-mounted (in-floor) slat conveyors use pit-mounted return runs so the top slat surface is flush with the factory floor for ergonomic loading.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Typical speed ranges for assembly slat conveyors against Richards-Wilcox and Pacline published data -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

