        Maintenance <span class="text-accent">Guide</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Chain lubrication:</strong> Roller chains require regular lubrication to prevent pin and bushing wear. Automatic chain lubrication systems apply metered oil or grease to the chain at set intervals. Manual lubrication works for short, accessible conveyors but is inconsistent and labor-intensive. Food-grade applications use H1 food-grade lubricants per NSF/USDA standards.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Chain elongation:</strong> Chains stretch (elongate) as pins and bushings wear. Measure chain pitch at regular intervals. Replace the chain when elongation exceeds 3% of the original pitch. Excessive elongation causes poor sprocket engagement, chain jump, and uneven slat spacing. Always replace both strands simultaneously to maintain synchronization.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Slat inspection:</strong> Check slats weekly for damage, warping, loose bolts, and excessive wear. Replace individual damaged slats without removing the entire chain. Wood slats require checking for splitting, moisture damage, and fastener pull-out. Steel slats require checking for bending, weld cracks, and corrosion.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Track and sprocket wear:</strong> Chain track rails wear from continuous chain contact. Worn tracks cause chain sag, noise, and misalignment. Replaceable wear strips on track rails extend frame life. Sprocket teeth wear from chain engagement. Replace sprockets when tooth profiles show visible wear or the chain no longer seats fully in the tooth pocket.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

