            What is a slat conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A conveyor using individual rigid slats (steel, wood, or plastic) attached to two parallel roller chains. The slats form a flat, stable platform for heavy loads (500-10,000+ lbs). Used in automotive assembly, appliance manufacturing, pallet handling, and any application needing a rigid conveying surface.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Slat conveyor vs. belt conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Slat conveyors use rigid slats on chains for heavy loads, heat resistance, and assembly fixturing. Belt conveyors use a flexible belt for lighter loads at lower cost. Choose slat for pallets, heavy products, and assembly lines. Choose belt for packages, parts, and general material handling.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What materials are slat conveyors made from?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Steel (carbon or stainless) for heavy loads and heat. Wood (hardwood) for pallets and finished products. Aluminum for cleanroom and lightweight applications. UHMW-PE plastic for food-grade and non-marring applications. Chain and frame are typically steel regardless of slat material.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What industries use slat conveyors?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Automotive assembly, appliance manufacturing, pallet handling, food processing, furniture manufacturing, and heavy industrial applications. Any industry needing a rigid, heavy-duty surface for large, heavy, or hot products.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

